    "5843569": {
      "title": "Influence of HIV infection on the response to interferon therapy and the long-term outcome of chronic hepatitis B",
      "abstract": "Background & Aims: The outcome of chronic hepatitis B and the efficacy of interferon alfa (IFN-) remain controversial in human immunodeficiency virus (HIV)-positive patients. We analyzed the influence of HIV coinfection on the response to IFN- therapy, long-term virologic status, progression to cirrhosis, and mortality. Methods: This was a retrospective follow-up cohort study of 141 consecutive hepatitis B e antigen–positive patients (69 HIV positive) followed up for 45 months. Results: The short-term response to IFN- therapy was not significantly different in HIV-positive and HIV-negative patients (28% vs. 51%; P 0.06) but was poorer in cases of low CD4 cell count (P 0.038). The hepatitis B virus (HBV) reactivation rate was higher in HIV-positive patients (P 0.033) and was associated with low CD4 cell count. The risk of cirrhosis was higher in HIV-positive patients with a CD4 cell count <200/mm 3 (relative risk"
    }
  },
